To evaluate  
\[
\lim_{x\to 4}\frac{4 - x}{\sqrt{x} - 2}
\]
we first observe that direct substitution gives \(0/0\), so we must algebraically simplify.  A convenient trick is to “rationalize” the denominator:

\[
\frac{4 - x}{\sqrt{x} - 2}
\;\times\;
\frac{\sqrt{x} + 2}{\sqrt{x} + 2}
\;=\;
\frac{(4 - x)\,(\sqrt{x} + 2)}{(\sqrt{x}-2)(\sqrt{x}+2)}
\;=\;
\frac{(4 - x)\,(\sqrt{x} + 2)}{x - 4}.
\]

Since \(4 - x = -\,(x - 4)\), this becomes

\[
\frac{-\,(x - 4)\,(\sqrt{x} + 2)}{x - 4}
\;=\;
-\;(\sqrt{x} + 2),
\]
for \(x\neq 4\).  Hence the original expression equals \(-(\sqrt{x}+2)\) when \(x\neq4\), and so

\[
\lim_{x\to 4}\frac{4 - x}{\sqrt{x} - 2}
\;=\;
-\bigl(\sqrt{4}+2\bigr)
\;=\;
-(2+2)
\;=\;
-4.
\]
